    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-31T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-31T18:00:00-05:00" n="1061"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1061">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114 Supplies/7–1544: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-31T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 31, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1825. ReDepts 1708 and 1709 of July 15. You will note that the Japanese
                    Government is ready to transship mail as well as relief supplies. If the consent
                    of the Soviet Government is received to the conditions set forth in the Japanese
                    reply, you are requested to endeavor to obtain the Soviet Government’s
                    authorization for United States’ authorities immediately to load on Soviet
                    vessels bound for Vladivostok mail for prisoners of war and civilian internees
                    for transshipment on the Japanese vessel at Nakhodka.<note n="96"
                        xml:id="d1061fn1">Ambassador Harriman reported in telegram 3200, August 28,
                        1944, that he had sent a note asking that Soviet vessels from the United
                        States west coast to Vladivostok be authorized to carry mail for American
                        prisoners of war and civilian internees in Japan (711.94114
                        Supplies/8–2844).</note> This shipment of mail is meant to be supplementary
                    to and not to replace the regular mail routed via Teheran and Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
